ngdom","Burleigh, Gloucestershire, England":"Burleigh, Gloucestershire, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"1338–Abt 1420":"1338–okolo 1420","1338–1420":"1338–1420","1340–1395":"1340–1395","1370–1475":"1370–1475","1265–Male":"1265–Zesnulý","1268–Female":"1268–Zesnulá","1338":"1338","1268":"1268","Abt 1354":"okolo 1354","Abt 1420":"okolo 1420","1475":"1475","1420":"1420","1265":"1265","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","liv. abt. 1420":"okolo 1420","Eng.":"Anglie, United Kingdom",", , England":"Anglie, United Kingdom","England":"Anglie, United Kingdom","Burleigh, Gloucestershire, England":"Burleigh, Gloucestershire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1338–Abt 1420":"1338–omkring 1420","1338–1420":"1338–1420","1340–1395":"1340–1395","1370–1475":"1370–1475","1265–Male":"1265–Afdød","1268–Female":"1268–Afdød","1338":"1338","1268":"1268","Abt 1354":"omkring 1354","Abt 1420":"omkring 1420","1475":"1475","1420":"1420","1265":"1265","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","liv. abt. 1420":"omkring 1420","Eng.":"England, United Kingdom",", , England":"England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Burleigh, Gloucestershire, England":"Burleigh, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1338–Abt 1420":"1338–circa 1420","1338–1420":"1338–1420","1340–1395":"1340–1395","1370–1475":"1370–1475","1265–Male":"1265–Overleden","1268–Female":"1268–Overleden","1338":"1338","1268":"1268","Abt 1354":"circa 1354","Abt 1420":"circa 1420","1475":"1475","1420":"1420","1265":"1265","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","liv. abt. 1420":"circa 1420","Eng.":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk",", , England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Burleigh, Gloucestershire, England":"Burleigh, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1338–Abt 1420":"1338–about 1420","1338–1420":"1338–1420","1340–1395":"1340–1395","1370–1475":"1370–1475","1265–Male":"1265–Deceased","1268–Female":"1268–Deceased","1338":"1338","1268":"1268","Abt 1354":"about 1354","Abt 1420":"about 1420","1475":"1475","1420":"1420","1265":"1265","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","liv. abt. 1420":"about 1420","Eng.":"England, United Kingdom",", , England":"England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Burleigh, Gloucestershire, England":"Burleigh, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin), French, and German: from the personal name <i>Giselbert</i>, composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>gīsil</i> ‘pledge, hostage, noble youth’ (see   Giesel  ) + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This personal name enjoyed considerable popularity in England during the Middle Ages, partly as a result of the fame of Saint Gilbert of Sempringham (1085–1189), the founder of the only native English monastic order.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","History: The Devon family of Gilbert can be traced to Geoffrey Gilbert (died 1349), who represented Totnes in Parliament in 1326. His descendants included Sir Humphrey Gilbert (died 1583), who discovered Newfoundland. — Étienne Gilbert from Aulnay in Vienne, France, married Marguerite Thibault in Neuville, QC, in 1683. Louis Gilbert <i>dit</i> Comtois from Besançon in Doubs married Anne Jacques in Charlesbourg, QC, in 1722. Pierre Gilbert from Barbezieux-Saint-Hilaire in Charente, France, married Marie-Angélique Dufour in Petite-Rivière-Saint-François, QC, in 1756. Charles Dupuis <i>dit</i> Gilbert from Rosnay in Indre, France, married Marie-Jeanne Brunet in Sainte-Foy, QC, in 1741."],"variants":[{"name":"Gieseke","meanings":["North German: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Giselbert</i> (see   Gilbert  ). Compare   Giesecke  ."]},{"name":"Giliberto","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Sal, Salvatore, Constantino, Costantino, Emilio, Rosario, Santo, Sebastiano, Vittorio.","Italian: from an ancient Germanic personal name (see   Gilbert  )."]},{"name":"Gipp","meanings":["English (East Anglia): from the personal name <i>Gipp</i>, a pet form of   Gilbert  . See also   Gibbs  . Alternatively, if pronounced with a soft <i>g</i>, it is a variant of <b>Jepp</b>, from the Middle English personal name <i>Jep(p)</i>, <i>Gep(pe)</i>, a pet form of   Jeffrey  .","German: from a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with the stem <i>geb</i> ‘gift’, as in <i>Gebhard</i> (see   Gebhardt  )."]},{"name":"Gilbertson","meanings":["English (northern): from the personal name   Gilbert   + <i>-son</i>."]},{"name":"Giesel","meanings":["German: from the personal name <i>Giesel</i>, a short form of any of several ancient Germanic personal names with the first element <i>gīsil</i> ‘pledge, hostage, noble offspring’. In ancient and medieval ancient Germanic society, the younger children of kings and princes were sometimes sent to be brought up at the court of a neighboring ruler, as a pledge of peace between the two nations or clans. Thus, the male personal name <i>Gisil</i> and its feminine equivalent <i>Gisela</i> mean both ‘pledge’ and ‘noble offspring’."]},{"name":"Gilb","meanings":["German: from a short form of the personal name   Gilbert  ."]},{"name":"Gibert","meanings":["French and German: from a shortened form of the personal name   Gilbert  . This name was also brought to England by Huguenot refugees in the 17th century.","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Giese","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Klaus, Erwin, Heiner, Heinz, Uwe, Aloysius, Armin, Dieter, Erhard, Ewald, Frieda.","German, Dutch, and Danish: from a short form of the personal name <i>Giselbert</i> (see   Gilbert  ), or any other ancient Germanic name with <i>gīsil</i> ‘hostage, pledge, noble offspring’ (see   Giesel  ) as the first element. Compare   Giesey  ."]},{"name":"Gibby","meanings":["English (Pembrokeshire): from a Middle English pet form of the personal name   Gilbert  ."]},{"name":"Gebbie","meanings":["Scottish (Ayrshire and Lanarkshire): from a pet form of the Norman personal name <i>Giselbert</i> (see   Gilbert  )."]}]},{"name":"Margred","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Margaret</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Mared","meanings":["Simplified form of   Marged ."]}]},{"name":"Wynston","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Although there was an Old English personal name, <i>Wynnstan</i>, from <i>wynn</i> ‘joy’ + <i>stān</i> ‘stone’, which would have had this form if it had survived, the modern given name is a transferred use of the surname, a local name from <i>Winston</i> in Gloucestershire. Use as a given name originated in the Churchill family: the first  Winston Churchill  (  b. 1620 ) was baptized with the surname of his mother's family. The name has continued in the family ever since, and has been widely adopted in honour of the statesman  Winston Spencer Churchill  (  1874–1965 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margred Wynston verch Gilbert was born in 1338, her father, Sir Gilbert Wynston, was 73 and her mother, Abrahall, was 71. She married Thomas Cecil about 1354. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1420, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 83."},"et":{"1338–Abt 1420":"1338–umbes 1420","1338–1420":"1338–1420","1340–1395":"1340–1395","1370–1475":"1370–1475","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1268–Female":"1268–Surnud","1338":"1338","1268":"1268","Abt 1354":"umbes 1354","Abt 1420":"umbes 1420","1475":"1475","1420":"1420","1265":"1265","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","liv. abt. 1420":"umbes 1420","Eng.":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom",", , England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Burleigh, Gloucestershire, England":"Burleigh, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1338–Abt 1420":"1338–noin 1420","1338–1420":"1338–1420","1340–1395":"1340–1395","1370–1475":"1370–1475","1265–Male":"1265–Kuollut","1268–Female":"1268–Kuollut","1338":"1338","1268":"1268","Abt 1354":"noin 1354","Abt 1420":"noin 1420","1475":"1475","1420":"1420","1265